h more modest than the profound social transformations the movement claims to support.There has been scant real-world assessment of Fair Trade’s effectiveness. Drawing upon fine-grained anthropological studies of a variety of regions and commodity systems including Darjeeling tea, coffee, crafts, and cut flowers, the chapters in Fair Trade and Social Justice represent the first works to use ethnographic case studies to assess whether the Fair Trade Movement is actually achieving its goals.Contributors: Julia Smith, Mark Moberg, Catherine Ziegler , Sarah Besky, Sarah M. Lyon, Catherine S. Dolan, Patrick C. Wilson, Faidra Papavasiliou, Molly Doane, Kathy M’Closkey, Jane Henrici  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aCompetition, Unfair. 0aInternational trade. 0aSocial justice. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBesky, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoane, Molly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolan, Catherine S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenrici, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyon, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyon, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoberg, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aM’Closkey, Kathy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPapavasiliou, Faidra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilson, Patrick C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZiegler, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTi